11. A method of predicting the future sensory state of a sensorimotor control system in a subject, comprising:
obtaining the Jacobian matrices for sensory states G(t) and motor control B(t), respectively, stored by the system;
obtaining a control vector u(t) describing the neural motor commands dictating a desired motion or task of the system, the desired motion or task being described by a reference trajectory r(t);
computing the delayed sensory state described by vector x(t−τ) using the values of G(t), B(t), and u(t);
estimating, based on G(i), B(t), and u(t), the time delay {circumflex over (τ)} of the system for performing the desired motion; and
predicting the future sensory state of the system described by vector {circumflex over (x)}(t),
the computing of the delayed sensory state vector x(t−τ) comprising the use of the following equation:


\({x\left( {t - \tau} \right)} = {{{G\left( {t - \tau} \right)}x_{0}} + {{G\left( {t - \tau} \right)}{\int_{0}^{t - \tau}{{G^{- 1}(s)}{B(s)}{u(s)}{ds}}}}}\)
where x0 is an initial sensory state, and
where t is time and τ is the actual time delay.

